{"id":"nucl-th/9811015","submitter":"Dr. Christoph Hartnack","authors":"C. Hartnack, Rajeev K. Puri, J. Aichelin, J. Konopka, S.A. Bass, H.\n  Stoecker, W. Greiner","title":"Modelling the many-body dynamics of heavy ion collisions: Present status\n  and future perspective","comments":"39 pages, 12 figures","journal-ref":"Eur.Phys.J.A1:151-169,1998","doi":"10.1007/s100500050045","report-no":null,"categories":"nucl-th","license":null,"abstract":"  Basic problems of the semiclassical microscopic modelling of strongly\ninteractingsystems are discussed within the framework of Quantum Molecular\nDynamics (QMD). This model allows to study the influence of several types of\nnucleonic interactions on a large variety of observables and phenomena\noccurring in heavy ion collisions at relativistic energies.It is shown that the\nsame predictions can be obtained with several -- numerically completely\ndifferent and independently written -- programs as far as the same model\nparameters are employed and the same basic approximations are made. Many\nobservables are robust against variations of the details of the model\nassumptions used. Some of the physical results, however, depend also on rather\ntechnical parameters like the preparation of the initial configuration in phase\nspace. This crucial problem is connected with the description of the ground\nstate of single nuclei,which differs among the various approaches. An outlook\nto an improved molecular dynamics scheme for heavy ion collisions is given.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 4 Nov 1998 15:23:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2014-11-18"}
{"id":"physics/9811007","submitter":"Harel Primack","authors":"Harel Primack and Reinhold Bl\\\"umel","title":"Synchrotron radiation of crystallized beams","comments":"REVTeX, 27 pages, 6 figures, submitted to Phys. Rev. E","journal-ref":"Phys.Rev. E60 (1999) 957-967","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevE.60.957","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.acc-ph physics.class-ph physics.plasm-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  We study the modifications of synchrotron radiation of charges in a storage\nring as they are cooled. The pair correlation lengths between the charges are\nmanifest in the synchrotron radiation and coherence effects exist for\nwavelengths longer than the coherence lengths between the charges. Therefore\nthe synchrotron radiation can be used as a diagnostic tool to determine the\nstate (gas, liquid, crystal) of the charged plasma in the storage ring. We show\nalso that the total power of the synchrotron radiation is enormously reduced\nfor crystallized beams. This opens the possibility of accelerating particles to\nultra-relativistic energies using small-sized cyclic accelerators.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 3 Nov 1998 16:37:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2009-10-31"}
